\begin_layout Part
Notes on Expenditure Elasticities in Africa
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Demand Analysis - Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The marketing and supply concerns have been ignored for the current stage
 of the study.
 The study of demand encompasses the household surveys in Tanzania and UK
 - inspecting the income elasticities of chosen commodities.
 The analysis focuses on Engel curves for the commodities and temporarily
 avoids the time-series analysis of incomes and prices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Cross Section Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a population is observed for a sufficiently long time, then we can understand
 the effects of changing incomes, price variations on their choices.
 A significant degree of demand analysis from panel data comes out of the
 Slutsky equation approach (e.g.
 the well-known AIDS model - a particular version of the Rotterdam model).
 With no time-series data, on the other hand, one relies on price-variations
 within the cross-section and interpretations of commodity-elasticities
 (instead of effects of changing income on a monitored household).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By adding more parameters to the semi-logarithmic model, one runs the risk
 of overfitting.
 It is easy, in other words, to stress on transient parameters in a given
 cross-sectional snapshot.
 The calibration of a cost-function and imposition of general conditions
 on the demand equations can get around some of these problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
A brief survey of household consumption models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Analysis by Prais-Houthakker
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Houthakker attributes the popularity of Engel curves to the idea of equivalence
 scales (i.e.
 how different households achieve same level of living standard).
 Although Houthakker's Engel fitting would now be considered unashamedly
 pragmatic 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonHandbook"

\end_inset

, his research was influential in popularising the use of income and expenditure
 elasticities in cross-sectional analyses 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HouthakkerFamilySurvey"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest Engel curves are set up with the Woking-Leser model hitherto
 used in the study:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w_{i}=\beta\cdot log\ x_{i}+\alpha
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, budget share total expenditure 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\sum p_{i}q_{i}$
\end_inset

, budget share
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}=p_{i}q_{i}/x$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 are regression coefficients.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A noticeable shortcoming with the Woking-Leser model is that no commodity
 specific information is used in the semi-logarithmic equation.
 The current study attempts to enhance this model with household and geographic
 parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cost Function and the Gorman Model 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Gorman approach considers a more general Engel curve: 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}=\sum_{r\epsilon R}a_{ir}(p)\Phi_{r}(ln(x))$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a finite set and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{r}(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 are general functions).
 For these to be consistent, one arrives at the cost function: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\ ln\ c(u,p)}{\partial\ ln\ p_{i}}=\sum_{r\epsilon R}a_{ir}(p)\Phi_{r}\{ln\ c(u,p)\}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $u=$
\end_inset

utility, 
\begin_inset Formula $p=$
\end_inset

price).
 Gorman derives following restrictions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{n}(\cdot)$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
w_{i} & =a_{i}(p)+b_{i}(p)ln\ x+d_{i}(p)\sum_{m=1}^{M}\gamma_{m}(p)(ln\ x)^{m}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
w_{i} & =a_{i}(p)+b_{i}(p)\sum_{\sigma_{m}\epsilon S_{-}}\mu_{m}(p)x^{\sigma_{m}}+d_{i}(p)\sum_{\sigma_{m}\epsilon S_{+}}^{M}\theta_{m}(p)x^{\sigma_{m}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a finite set of elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{-}$
\end_inset

 its negative elements and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{+}$
\end_inset

positive (
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 leads us back to Working-Leser form).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum a_{i}(p)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum b_{i}(p)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Gorman model combines 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

demographic scaling
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

demographic translating
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PollockWalesDemand"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A significant amount of research has been done in scaling of the individual
 model (through the analysis of the so-called cost-of-children problem).
 Muellbauer has enhanced the model by considering every household a multiple
 of unit 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{h}$
\end_inset

 (individual).
 One considers a multiplicative index 
\begin_inset Formula $m(a^{h},u^{h})$
\end_inset

such that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
c^{h}(u^{h},p,a^{h}) & =m(a^{h},u^{h})\cdot c(u^{h},p)
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $c(u^{h},p)$
\end_inset

 is the cost-function for every household.
 The budget share 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}^{h}$
\end_inset

is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{h}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w_{i}^{h}=\frac{ln\ c(u^{h},p)}{\partial\ ln\ p_{i}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With derivatives with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{h}$
\end_inset

, Muellbauer further uses the above equation (and PIGLOG functions) to study
 the Barten's model for cost-of-having-children 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MuellbauerBartenModel"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Testing Spatial Variation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An analysis of expensive vs non-expensive food items was done by Prais and
 Houthakker (1955)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HouthakkerFamilySurvey"

\end_inset

.
 This has been employed for LSMS data in the current study.
 To address spatial variations, Deaton use the following model for a cluster-bas
ed analysis:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
ln\ q_{Gic} & =\alpha_{G}^{0}+\beta_{G}^{0}ln\ x_{ic}+\gamma_{G}^{0}\cdot z_{ic}+\sum_{H=1}^{5}\theta_{GH}ln\ p_{Hc}+(f_{Gc}+u_{Gic}^{0})
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
ln\ v_{Gic} & =\alpha_{G}^{1}+\beta_{G}^{1}\ ln\ x_{ic}+\gamma_{G}^{1}\cdot z_{ic}+\sum_{H=1}^{5}\psi_{GH}ln\ p_{Hc}+u_{Gic}^{1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, quantity of good 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 consumed by cluster 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{Gic}$
\end_inset

, the associated unit-value is 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{Gic}$
\end_inset

, total expenditure is 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{Gic}$
\end_inset

, a vector of household demographic characteristics is 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{Gic}$
\end_inset

.
 Two error terms used consist of i) a cluster-specific random effect 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{Gc}$
\end_inset

along with the error 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{Gic}^{0}$
\end_inset

and ii) idiosyncratic error
\begin_inset Formula $u_{Gic}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The computation of variance-covariance vectors
\begin_inset Formula $u^{0}$
\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula $u^{1}$
\end_inset

is used to derive cluster effects e.g.
 inter-cluster variances and covariances for the separable goods.
\end_layout

