\begin_layout Subsection
Analysis and Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Without a survey (which validates both the visibility of the item and its
 association with high-income), our criterion involves looking at the income
 elasticity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The critieria for inclusion is the extent to which a commodity is used is
 important.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a commodity is only used by richer sections of society, then it should
 be ignored for our analysis - since we're interested only in congestion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any product used by everybody can potentially cause congestion.
 How a commodity is classified (as something widely consumed) can drive
 the notion of congestion.
 A wider (loose) category can be considered a case for congestion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Congestion is psychological because it represents a need felt.
 The degree of how widely a commodity is used - loosely represents the competiti
on (thus the congestion) for it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The competition or congestion is always for a product - a product that is
 used sufficiently widely.
 Housing is used throughout but nicer houses could be congested (neighborhoods
 and other status drivers would represent both drive status and consumotion).
 Just recording the housing expense doesn't capture congestion for nicer
 houses.
 If the data was available for a region where housing is known to be limited,
 then one can say that there is a congestion.
 If two groups A and B with same level of disparity in income amidst them
 (
\begin_inset Formula $income_{A}>income_{B})$
\end_inset

, then they would have different choices in areas where there is congestion
 for a commodity available.
 The analysis in regions might show this phenomenon in more detail.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The essential feature is that of feedback.
 Both consumption and status drive each other.
 If we measure status (by looking at a range of product classifications
 e.g.
 the range of nicer to worse neighborhoods) and then measure the widespread
 consumption on them, it must be noted that the higher consumption is what
 people are opting for.
 It's not as if people spend more on nicer housing for higher status alone
 - it's them being able to spend higher that becomes higher status.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Social barriers need to be seen characteristics of the utility function.
 Congestion is faced differently by differenct social classes (a particular
 class may not feel the need to have conspicuous consumption or the social
 barriers can limit the need for conspicuous consumption)\SpecialChar \@.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Income data includes categories like unpaid family work.
 The predominance of informal sector means that occupations are neither
 well defined nor an indicator of total income.
 Even people with no-job have income from secondary work.
 Paid family work and agriculture are under same categories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While joining results, two products can be combined only when the extent
 of their usage is similar.
 The aggregate of all categories could be looked at without this restriction
 of joining.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A core of the current theory is crowding - therefore the effect of population
 density on visible / industrial consumption needs to be inspected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
English speaking doesn't affect results for most part.
 Speaking English doesn't mean being progressive.
 Region is endogenous for housing - for which only the housing status drives
 expenditure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Skincream might have an appeal for - but it is by no means associated with
 high-income.
 Some analysis includes it while other doesn't.
 Only a survey can tell whether people associate an item with a survey or
 not.
\end_layout

